{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_quarren_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280658832/1913111601/0706.xml":{"full_text":"MARKET IS DULL;\nBUYERS ARE WARY\nLack of Demand. More Than\nPressure to Sell, Respon\nsible for Stagnation.\nNEWS AS TO MEXICO\nNOW A PRIME FACTOR\nInvestors Disposed to Await De\nvelopments as to Relations With\nSouthern Republic.\nNKW YORK, November 13.?Trading in\n?to'k^ was light throughout the half-day\nsession which brought the week to an\nrrfi, and in most rases net changes were\nonly nominal. After a firm opening the\nmarket became heavy, more because of a\nlark of demand than from any marked\npressure.\nInvestment buyers held aloof Specula\ntors worked with caution, being inclined\nto take the bear side because of the\nfcbsense of support and the continued\nweakness of various stocks, such as\nMissouri Pacific. Ne? Haven and Lehigh\nValley. Losses were small, however, an-;\nthey wore largely made up on s<''v\nbuying toward th. close Lehigh alley\nwas heavy throughout. New Havend>.\nplicated its daily performance recently b>\nmaking a low record, At io.\nPaclfl?\\ iit 4-47s, was at. the >e?trs lowtbt.\nAwaits Mexican Developments.\nThere was a general disposition to\nfcwait developments in regard to Mexican\nn ffairs over the week end. and business\nwas restricted by this consideration. The\nday wat barren of news with an influence\non market values, with the exception of\nfurther pessimistic ri ports from the steel\nuade The weekly reviews of trade cor.\ni.itions referred to lessened commercial\nactlv.tv )n various lines.\nThe bank statement made the expected\nK..,d showing. There was an\ntain in urency of more than $l-,<JOtMWO\nand $7.*.~>3.00? was added to the surplus.\nThe recent improvement in the position of\nth.- banks, together with the easing of\nmont'V rates, indicates that the autumn\nmand: upon the money market have\npassed their hi^h point, and that in all\nprobability fairly easy conditions will\nprevail during the remainder of the year.\nNot Cause of Anxiety.\nNo difficulties are now anticipated in\nconnection with December 1 payments,\nalthough preparations for meeting these\nr?<tu:r>-ments may produce a temporary\nstiffening in call funds. The bond mar\nket was irregular, with heaviness in some\nweli known issues. Total sales, par value,\n?h>.\nr. .S. 4s advanced '-i- on call on the\nv eek.\nExpect New Business.\nrile steel companies are building great\nexpectations of new business upon the\nfact that stocks of rolled products in\nthe hands of merchants and distr buters\nIn the interior are depleted, it being only\na question of time when new buying will\nbe inaugurated. Last week's orders, how\never, were not encouraging, and with\nspecifications even smaller mill and fur\nnace operations were further reductd. As\na whole the industry is operating l.ttle\nwore than per cent of capacity. Some\nlines of manufacture, as shetts and tin\nplate. have little over 50 per cent of ca\npacity active.\nThe October statement of the steel\n?orporatlon indicated that new orders\nlast month were less than 500.000 tons,\nor scarcely 4o per cent of finished capac\nity It is believed that November will\nmake a better showing.\nThe railroads have suddenly ceased\nactive interest in structural work, appro\npriations for such work for 1*J13 having\nbeen expended. The only important rail\ncontract last week was 50,<h., tons for\nthe Louisville and Nashville. Orders for\ncars and locomotives were insignificant.\nSteel building work was sharply con\ntracted. while competition for steel orders\na as keen and lower prices prevailed The\n1 ig iron trade was f'.at and prices again\n<1 upped .V? cents per ton last week in all\ni tions.\nNEW YORK PRODUCE.\nNEW YORK, November 15.?Flour?\nQuiet\nRye flour?Quiet.\nforum* al?Steady.\nRye?Qu et.\nBarley?Steady.\nWheat?Spot firm; No. 2 red. 97M?\nnominal c.i.f. New York export basis\nand a9c fob. afloat: No. I northern l.?u\nluth, i*5'~ f.o.b. afloat. Futures firm on\nthe cables an