ls Southwestern con. 4* *70\nSeal>oard Air Line adj. 5s 72%\nSouthern Pacific col. 4a 01\nSouthern Pacific cv. 4s S4%\nSouthern pacific R R. 1st ref. 4a 9U\nSouthern Railway .\"Is l'Vtt^\nSouthern Railway gen. 4h 73%\nI Pnlon Pacific 4s !*4%\nFnlon Pacific cv. 4s OO\n1'nion Pacific 1st and ref. 4s 1)2\nV*. S. Rubber 6s 101M,\nI*. S. Steel 2d 5s\nVirginia-Carolina Chemical 3s *!I3\ni Wabash 1st ami ext. 4s *4S\nj Western Maryland 4s *76%\nWestlnghoiise Electric ov. 5a ill\nj Wisconsin Central 4s 85%\nI 'Bid. t Offered.\nBoston Closing: Mining.\nBOSTON. November 15.\nillouez 2?^\nAmalgamated Copper Oij\ni American Zinc, Lead Sto. 17%\nI Arizona Commercial 4%\nBos. Corb. Cop. SIX. Mg fiOe\nI Calumet Arizona\nj Calumet A. Hecla 4?>5\nI Centennial 12%\nCopper Range Con. Co 30%\nKast Butte Cop Mine 10%\nFranklin 3\ntlranbv Consolidated Of\ni Greene-Cananea... 31\nIsle Roy all- (Copper) 17%\nKerr Lake. 4%\nLake Copper OV*\nl a SalU Copper 3%\nMiami Copper 21\nMohawk 40Vi\nNevada Consolidated 14%\nNipisslng Mines 8 3-10\nI North Butte 23\nNorth Lake 1%\nOid Dominion 48\nOweol* J2\nQulncy 85\nShannon\nSuperior 22\nSuperior A Boston Mln\nTamarack 27\nV. S Sm., Ref. and M'n 37\nl!. S. Sm.. Ref. and MiD. pfd 47\nFtah Consolidated S'-i\nI'tah Copper Co 49\nWinona 1%\nWolverine 41\nDRY GOODS MARKET.\nNEW YORK. November 15.?Cotton\npoods markets are very steady. New un\n1 derwear lines have been opened for fall\nat price advances ranging from 12%\ncents to 25 cents a dozen. Burlaps are\nfirmer. Linens, are strong\nTypewriter Theft Is Charged.\nMitchell Brown, colored. '-*028 F street\nnorthwest, was arrested last night by\nPoliceman Stroman of the third precinct\nand charged with larceny from the\nUnited States. It is alleged that he\ntook a condemned typewriter *from the\nMills building, where he was employed,\nand took it to a local establishment,\nwhere he ordered it repaired. The po\nlice .-ay Brown told them lie thought\n|ho typewriter was of no value*\nSTOCK UST GAINS\nIN GENERAL LEVEL\nHope of Mexican Solution\nWithout War Adds to\nMarket Confidence.\nSTEEL MARKET SHOWS\nLET-UP IN BUSINESS\nWorkers Are Laid OIF, Despite Les\nsened Fears of Effects of\nNew Tariff.\nNEW YORK, November 15.?The highly\nIrregular character of the stock market\nthis week reflected a continuance of the\nuncertainty which has been felt for some\ntime past as to the outlook. The great\nquestions confronting the financial world,\nrelating to international monetary condi\ntions, political complications and the busi\nness situation, remained unsolved.\nThe stock market, nevertheless, showed\na definite Improvement on the week. It\nbenefited from the hopes of settlement of\nthe Mexican problem without military\nintervention such as would withdraw gold\nfrom Europe and upset the money mar\nkets.\nIn all markets there were indications of\na liquidated condition, and of watchful\nness for signs of revival. Great import\nance was attached to the outcome of the\nforthcoming French loan for $280,000,000,\nwhich, .it is hoped, will unlock hoarded\ncapital besides. In this country increas\ning dependence is placed upon allowance\nof higher railroad freight rates to stimu\nlate investment markets.\nLessened Fears of Tariff.\nLaying off of steel workers Indicated\nthat the recession in that trade waa still\nin progress. Firmer German steel mar\nkets lessened fears of foreign competition\nas a result of tariff changes. Further\nprice concessions were announced by\ndomestic producers. Weakness of re\nfined copper pointed to conditions in that\ntrade paralleling those in the steel in\ndustry.\nThe snowstorm increased the costs of\nrailroad operations, j tout (stimulated a\nseasonable demand for merchandise, and\nresulted in an improvement in crop pros\npects. The large acreage sown to winter\nwheat entered into speculative esti\nmates. The government's estimate of the\nlarge sum realized from the corn crop\nmeasured the compensation to farmers\nof the high price for the short crop.\nCOTTON MARKETS.\nNEW YORK.\nNEW YORK, November 15.?There was\nconsiderable realizing in the cotton mar\nket today. Offerings were well enough\nabsorbed, however, to give the market\na steady undertone, and the close was\nsteady at a net decline of twenty-three\npoints on November, but only five points\nunder the final figures of yesterday on\nactive months. Rumors that preliminary\nreturns to the National Ginners' Associa\ntion indicated that ginning for the last\nperiod, from November 1 to November\n14, had been 1,423,000 bales, or rather\nless than reflected by the private report\npublished yesterday, may have helped\nthe market somewhat in the late trading,\nas closing prices were two or three points\nup from the lowest.\nRelatively easy Liverpool cables pre\nceded the realizing movement here, and\nflrst prices were one to four points\nlower. There was some buying by\nhouses with German connections, as well\nas further covering of shorts and moder\nate support from local bulls, but after\nsome early Irregularity, prices gradually\nsagged off. with active months selling\nabout eight to ten points net lower late\nin the morning. Reviews of the domestic\ngoods trade indicated a fair demand for\nimmediate shipment at full prices, but\na poor demand for forward shipments,\nand it is said that in some Instances the\nmills are ready to grant concessions for\ncontracts. Fall River reports that a jaw\nmaterial stock sufficient J or tnret moifihs'\nrequirements is held by mills only in ex\nceptional cases.\nNEW ORLEANS.\nNEW ORLEANS. November lu.-LIqui\ndation of the long interest over the week\nend weighed against prices in the cot\nton market today. No real weakness\nwaa brought about and the decline was\ngeneral. Bears were not aggressive and\nmade no effort to take the advantage the\noffering from the long side gave them.,\nA feature was the rumor that a promi\nnent private bureau was out with a pre\nliminary estimate of the amount of cot\nton ginned up to November 13 of 10,\n.'135,000 bales. This was considered bull\nish, as it was In line with the predic\ntions of less conservative bulls, but it\ncaused no fresh buying of consequence.\nThe market opened steady, 1 point up\nto 2 points down. Cables were not as\nhigh as due, but there were enough\nbuying orders In brokers' hands to put\nprices 1 to 3 points over yeste day's\nclose around the first call. This was the\nhigh of the morning. The weather map\nwas favorable, no rains being reported,\nbut the outlook was for unsettled weather\nover Sunday. Private cable messages from\nLiverpool said that the market there\nhad been depressed by hedge selling. Sell\ning out by buyers of the earlier part of\nthe week was the deciding influence and\nprices fell off until toward noon they\nwere 10 points under the final quota\ntions of yesterday. The close was steady\nat a net loss of 7 to 8 points. Spot\ncotton closed quiet, unchanged: middling,\n13 5 18. Sales on the spot, 1,015 bales;\nto arrive, flOO.\nCotton futures closed: November,\n13.20; nominal; December, 13.36al3.37;\nJanuary, 13.41al3.48; March, 13.51al3.57;\nMay, 13.57al3.5S; July, 13.59al3.68.\nIt was a quiet week in the cotton mar\nket. Price changes were narrow. After\nthe middle of the week the market dis\nplayed some little activity and consider\nable firmness. The net result of the\nweek's trading was an advance of IS to\n2t? points. The high prices were made\nFriday, and the low prices Monday. At\nthe highest the trading months were 32 to\n44t points over last week's close: at the\nlowest they were 5 to S points under. The\nrange was 39 to 48 points.\nTrading was unimportant during the\nearly part of the week. Wednesday and\nThursday there were many reports that\npicking and ginning were nearing com\npletion, which the bulls accepted as proof\nof their small crop claims. On the re\nports the market did better. Friday a\nmaterial advance was caused by the\nmonthly report on consumption and.\nHester's weekly statement on mill tak\nings. The figures on consumption in this\ncountry of 542,809 bales during October,\nagainst 513,000 the same month last year,\nwere accepted as one of the most bullish\ndevelopments thus far this season.\nMill-taking statistics were in line with\nthe census figures and caused consider\nable buying on the theory that they\npointed to a continued large consumption\nfor November\nIn the spot department prices lost *4 of\na cent; middling closed at 13 5-16, against\n13 7-16 last week and 11\"b this week last\nyear Sales on the spot amounted to\n6,940 bales, against 5,099 last week and\n3,770 this week last year. Sales to ar\nrive amounted to 8.702 bales, against\n8.291 last week and 7,ti90 this week last\nyear.\nTo Address Mississippi Society.\nSenator Key Pittman of Nevada, a na\ntive of Vicksburg, Miss., is scheduled to\naddress the Mississippi Society on \"Alas\nka\"' Friday evening at Confederate Me\nmorial Hall, 1322 Vermont avenue north\nwest. Senator Pittman was the first\nprosecuting attorney at Nome, Alaska,\nand represented the mine owners in the\ncelebrated mining litigation.\nIf you want work, read the want coU\n,unma of The Sta&\nLEVEL OF PRICES\nLIFTED A TRIFLE!\nWeek's Activity Is Concen\ntrated Upon Old Group of\nHalf Dozen Favorites.\nMARKET HAS MOVED\nIN NARROW LIMITS\nPublic Still Cautious of Speculative\nOfferings?Mexico Street's\nMain Interest.\nBY W. G. NICHOLAS.\nSpecial Correspondence of The Star.\nNBW YORK, November 15,\nThe level of quotations was lifted mod\nerately this week, and revival of 1>ullish\nsentiment was proclaimed. Activity was i\nconcentrated upon the old gToup of half i\ndozen favorites, reinforced by a hand- j\nful of specialties- By common consent\nLiondon was given credit for leading the\nbuying1, being moved thereto by the\nalleged subsidence of Mexican belliger\nency, and also by the bright prospect of\ncurrency legislation during the life of\nthe special session of Congress. The rea\nsoning that resulted from the unexpect\ned allowance of $t*,000,000 additional\nwages for account of trainmen and con\nductors was that the interstate com\nmerce commission would be shown there\nby the imperative last-straw necessity\nof allowing the railroads an offsetting\n$50,<j00,000 freight rate raise.\nIt could not bo detected that the public\nwent wild over the developments of the\nweek, but some definite Improvement was\nclaimed by the bullishly inclined traders,\nand symptoms of public enlistment on\nthe buying Hide were observed at inter\nvals. Sporadic activity was made the\nmost of to arouse public interest, but\nstrange as it may see an overwhelming\nmajority of bankers arid brokers still\nadvise their friends and customers to\n\"keep out of the market.'' until \"condi\ntions take definite form.\" Asked for a\nbill of particulars or some \"definite\"\ninformation, the w'se men confess they\nare helpless as children; in desperation\nthey stick to the above quoted phrase.\nThere is nothing to take its place, thus\nfar. The limit of prices has been nar\nrow throughout the entire list, and ex\ncept for an occasional little rally sig\nnalizing usually the \"running in\" of a\ngroup of timid bears the play was fea\ntureless. Mexico furnished nearest ap\nproach to fireworkt.\nThe keenest among the students and\nprofessional traders confess frankly that\nthey do not know whether the market is\n\"overbought\" or \"oversold,\" and can\nnot find out. The expression is well nigh\nunanimous from the traders' standpoint\nthat the situatiftn is still a hopeless mys\ntery, and that news material for guid\nance is practically worthless.\nBargain Counter Full.\nThe market is \"chuck full\" of bar\ngains. Dozens of stocks that are nor\nmally appraised as gilt-edged 4M to H\nper cent dividend payers go begging at\n(i to S per cent, and even bonds con\ntinue to work lower under mysterious\npressure. The bravest \"plungers\" rarely\nrisk more than a few hundred shares,\nwhere it was formerly blocks of 10,000\nto 50.000 shares. Those who have money\nare suffering from confessed fiscal paral\nysis; those who have light capital (and\nthey are in overwhelming majority In\nthe Wall street district; are merely\nthin-voiced members of the stagnant\nhost and contribute nothing to the sum\nof gambling or investment intelligence.\nLiquidation for New England account\nis probably heaviest, reckoned on the\ndivideno sacrifice basis, and New Haven\nis not the only issue that has gone and\nis going to a \"meal ticket sacrifice.\"\nTens of millions in securities have been\nsold out to provide for the current needs\nof the \"poor investor (literally \"poor\"),\nand New England is the chief sufferer\nthus far And yet it must be confessed\nthat there are fundamental reasons for\nstock market and money market con\nstriction. The down turn has been fore\nshadowed for a long time by such\n\"seers\" as \"Jim'' Hill, Jacob SchifT. J.\nB. Forgan and others of that class.\nPersistent harping on the long unrec\nognized fact that the tight of radicalism\nagainst capital would sooner or later\ntake the form of a terribly dangerous\nagency .for the repression of enterprise,\ndestruction values and revolution of\nestablished business institutions may be\nregarded distasteful, but the dangerous\ngravity of the development is finally\ncoming to be generally recognized.\nAccumulated capital, to whose activity\nthe material progress of the country of\nrecent years has been and is largely\ndue, is threatened with confiscation and\nits owners with condign punishment.\nWholesale nervousness and actual fear\nare now in tangible evidence in the\ngiant maYkets. Hundreds and thousands\nof men compose a list of capitalists who\nwill not risk a dollar \"on a chance,\" as\nthey put it. A condition of rank apathy\nhas been created. Prevailing sullenness,\nthat Is disheartening in the extreme,\nrules, and *rom it there is no present\nevidence of recovery.\nGary's Steel Claim Proven.\nWhen Judge Gary said repeatedly that\nthe United States Steel Corporation\ncould compete successfully with the best\nequipped European steel and iron mills\nregardless of tariffs, nine out of ten\ndoubted or openly disbelieved the claim.\nThe steady increase in the volume of\nAmerican exports during the last three\nyears (a large per cent originating with\nthe so-called Gary trust), has brou% it\nabout an overwhelming change of opin\nion. With quotations of product ruling\n$:i to $7 per ton lower than they did on\ntop level and \"trust\" exportatlons more\nthan doubled, the curious demanded how\nthe miracle could be done. The explana\ntion was easy, and it is no longer con\ncealed. For that matter it was never\nconcealed. The corporation simply went\nquietly along \"sawing wood and saying\nnothing.\"\nIt had been the custom of the levia\nthan producer to put back the best part\nof surplus earnings into plant and ex\npansion. In about eight years over $4o?>.\n000.000 of \"velvet\" went back that way.\nAbout two years ago a change of policy\nwas determined upon. It was decided\nthat there was no longer vital need for\nfurther large expenditure of earnings in\nplant and that the owners (the 125,000\nshareholders) had a right to share in\nthe future surplus earnings. The ?4o,\nOOO.OnjO to $50,000,000 subtracted annually\nfrom earnings and turned into Improve\nments and expansions was suddenly di\nverted to the pockets of the grand army\nof individual shareholders. The wonder\nful annual surplus could be spared for\nthe shareholders for a few years without\ndetriment to plant or Impairment to\nefficiency, and that is what is being done\nnow.\nIt was merely the legitimate diversion\nof a large fraction of the net earnings\nInto a different channel. By common\nconsent the United States Steel Corpora\ntion has $1 to $3.50 per ton the best of\ncompetition in home manufacture, and is\nproving by the figures of the custom\nhouses on both s*ides of the Atlantic that\nit can undersell the producers of Eng\nland, Germany and other European coun\ntries in their home markets.\nThe foregoing facts are not new to the\nhundreds of thousands of men In the\nsteel trade, but the genera! public has\nonlv a dim inkling of the true inward\nness. The history of the current year\nshows in black and white what can be\ndone in the saving of money, without\nImpairment of efficiency. Not even the\ndesperate determination of the govern\nmental law department to \"bust\" this\nparticular steel trust and put it out of\nbusiness seems to seriously disturb the\ngreat captains of industry in command.\nMany Dividend Earners.\nXfaero has probably never been go many\n4\nFINANCIAL.\nFINANCIAL\nFINANCIAL.\narasasLms\nOFFICERS:\nB. F. SAUL, President.\nJAMES F. SHEA, Vice President.\nALEX. S. CLARKE, Secretary.\nHOWARD MORAN, Treasurer.\nEDWARD E. SWAN, Asst. Treas.\nF. G. ADDISON, Jr., Asst. Treat.\nDIRECTORS:\nWILLIAM H. BURCH,\nALEX. S. CLARKE.\nANTHONY QAEGLER,\nJOHN B. BEIER,\nJ. P. HERRMANN,\nR. H. JOHNSON,\nWM. MILLER.\nHOWARD MORAN,\nJOHN H. RUPPERT.\nB. F. SAUL,\nW. E. SHANNON,\nJAMES F. SHEA,\nJOHN SHUGHRUE.\nUnder Supervision of the U.S. Treasury.\nHOME SAVINGS BANK\n7tb SI. nri Mm. *11. a.m.\nBRANCHES:\n8th N Sis. N.E. 436 7th St.\n3\nq1 Compound Interest paid on Sav\n/O ings Accounts, computed semi\nannually. Accounts opened with One\nDollar or over.\nQfl Compound Interest paid on In\nfO active Checking Accounts, such\nas personal accounts of individuals or\naccounts of trustees, executors, etc.\n2\nCommercial Accounts invited, and every accom\nmodation offered such depositors consistent with\nconservative banking.\nDrafts issued on all foreign countries, a!s<?\n\"A. A.\" and American Express Co. Travelers*\nChecks, payable in any part of the world.\nLoans made on first trust real estate, collaterals\nor othe^ good security. Monthly payment rea1\nestate l<^ans arranged.\nGas and Electric Light bills can be paid at any\nof our bank*- without extra cost. Receipts given.\nSafe Deposit Boxes for rent, $3.00 a year.\nBanking Hours:\nAlt departments are open every \\\\e*-k day. ex ept Satur\nday and Legral Holidays, from S:.'t0 A.M to .'t I'M.: Satur\nday, K:30 A.M. to 12 M.. and for deposits from to w iJ M\nand on the 1st 2d. ilw, 10th, 15th, lt>th a 11 I last day- of\neach month until P.M.\nproved dividend earners on the market at\nsuch low average quotations as now adorn\nthe lists. New Investors are in the mar\nket to some extent, but they are not un\ncountable in numbers or resistless in\nforce. They simply buy when favored\nspecialties look attractive, but they are\nseldom inspired with actual bullishness\nFew of them will a^mit they unticlpat'\nan earlv upward movement, but they\nhold to the theory that prices cannot sink\nmuch lower unless the whole country\ngoes to the dogs. Admittedly the l-'nited\nStates is the richest nation in the world,\nand it is hard to recognize the possibuity\nof a genuine panic in the near future.\nKven the most earnest preachers of the\ngospel of calamity have their limits, and\nthey confess that sooner or later they ex\npect a return of prosperity and popular\nserenity. Just now, however, they preter\nto feel bad.\nThe prophecy is oft heard that money\nwill be easy after the tirst of the year,\nand that stocks bought now and held\nstubbornly will yield large speculative\nprofits during the winter months. The\nJanuary distribution of interest and divi\ndends will total larger than on any pre\nvious date in the country's history, so the\nstatisticians say. That performance once\nover there should be the greatest loanab;e\ncapital ever accumulated in the banks of\nthe republic. It is not wholly improba\nble that the country will be the benefi\nciary of tremendous fiscal plenty instead\nof starving for meager accommodations,\nas so many profess to fear.\nWall street takes less interest in cur\nrency legislation than might be imagined.\nFew know just what the pending measure\naims at. and just how the business of the\ncountry is going to be benefited by its\npassage; consequently, outside of special\nists and politicians small interest Is shown\nin Washington bulletins on that subject.\nThere is not nearly as much excitement\nover currency developments as there is\nover the revolutionary performances south\nof the Rio Grande. The deep-sea think\ners are framing weird conjectures over\nthe International Influences that a first\nclass row with Mexico would generate.\nAt the moment, though, quotations are\nonly jumped up and down in nervous\nfractions over the bulletins of unrest\nBut somehow the war gossip fails to pro\nduce either volcanic booms or breaks on\nthe exchangt s.\nCurrencv partisanship is confined to lim\nited factions, and the spirit of conference\nseems to be grow ing warmer. Friends of\nthe President predict a series of con\nspicuous political triumphs during the en\nsuing year.\nWHOLESALE MARKET REPORT.\nQuotations given below are for large\nlots. Jobbers' prices are higher.\nEGGS?Strictly fresh Virginia, 3Ha40;\nnearbv. 37a38; West Virginia and south\nwest Virginia, 36; storage, 28a32.\nBUTTER?Elgin, fancy, per lb, 33%a\n34l-z; western firsts, 35Vs; second*, 32fea\n82Vfc.\nCHEESE?New York state factory,\nnew. 18.\nPOULTRY?Hens, per lb., 12al3; roost\ners. per lb., turkeys, per lb.. 16;\nchickens, per lb., 13a 1~<; ducks, per lb.,\n13a 14; keats, each, 25a50.\nDRESSED POULTRY?Hens, choice,\nper lb., 13; turkeys, per lb, 19; ducks,\nper lb., l-fal.r>; chickens, per lb., 17al8.\nGREEN FRUITS?Apples, box. 1.75a\n2 75\" bbl., 1.50a0.00; oranges, California,\nbox,' 5.00a6.50; Florida, ?er box, 2.50a\n3.00; lemons, per box, 3.50a4.50;\npineapples, per crate, 2.0<'a3.00; grape\n'ruit per box, 4.00a5.00; grapes. New York\nstate per 4-Ib. basket, Niagara, lsa20;\nConcords, 18a20; pears, per box, 1.25a2.50;\nchestnuts, per lb., 2a5; cranberries, per\nbbl., 7.00a8.00; per box, l.!?5a2.75.\nHAY AND STRAW?Hay, western.\nNo 1. 20.00a21.00; No. 2, 19.OOal0.50.\nmixed' hay